# Fluff Date: 2026-02-10 14:00:04
overview:<p>The Fire Moth, known by the Inner Sphere codename Dasher, is a 20-ton Clan OmniMech originally developed by Clan Cloud Cobra scientists in 2874. Conceived as an infantry support platform, the prototype featured underslung infantry pods on its distinctive high-mounted arms, designed to ease the battlefield deployment of Elementals. Though the pods were quickly abandoned after initial field testing (drawing derision from warriors who considered the concept impractical) the unusual arm configuration was retained, proving unexpectedly beneficial for armored infantry operations.</p><p>Clan Ghost Bear acquired the design through a five-year trade agreement with the Cloud Cobras, and the Fire Moth became a mainstay of Ghost Bear and Hell's Horses formations. One of the fastest OmniMechs ever produced, its extraordinary speed earned it the Dasher designation from Inner Sphere intelligence agencies, though its minimal armor and limited pod space largely restrict it to reconnaissance, scouting, and infantry support roles.</p>

capabilities:<p>Built around a 200-rated extralight fusion engine, the Fire Moth achieves a cruising speed of 108 kilometers per hour with a top speed of 162 kilometers per hour. A chassis-mounted MASC system pushes this to an extraordinary 216 kilometers per hour in short bursts, making the Fire Moth one of the fastest battlefield assets in any arsenal. This performance comes at significant cost: the endo steel chassis and two tons of IceSheet ferro-fibrous armor provide only token protection, leaving the Fire Moth dangerously vulnerable to even light weapons fire.</p><p>With just six and a half tons of pod space, weapon loadouts remain modest across all configurations. The Prime configuration exemplifies the design philosophy, mounting a pair of ER medium lasers alongside SRM-6 and SRM-4 launchers for a respectable short-range strike package. Ten double heat sinks handle the thermal demands of most configurations without difficulty. The Fire Moth's true value lies not in firepower but in its unmatched speed, allowing it to fulfill scouting, spotting, and rapid infantry deployment roles that heavier OmniMechs cannot match.</p>

deployment:<p>Introduced during the Dark Age, the Alternate Configuration G represents an extreme application of speed-enhancing technology. Four improved heavy medium lasers linked to a targeting computer deliver devastating firepower, while an engine supercharger supplements the chassis MASC to propel the Fire Moth to approximately 250 kilometers per hour in short bursts. A coolant pod helps manage the extreme thermal output of the heavy laser array. This configuration epitomizes the high-risk, high-reward philosophy favored by the most aggressive warriors.</p>

history:<p>The Fire Moth's origins trace to Clan Cloud Cobra's experimental weapons programs during the Golden Century. Scientists designed the OmniMech as a dedicated infantry support platform, but the radical arm-mounted infantry pod concept drew immediate ridicule from warriors who dismissed it as "crazy as a Mandrill idea." Persistent MASC reliability issues further complicated early development, and the Cloud Cobras ultimately traded the design to Clan Ghost Bear for five years of favorable trade considerations.</p><p>The Ghost Bears transformed the Fire Moth from a troubled prototype into a successful combat platform. Their scientists retained the elevated arm mounts after discovering that accidental battle damage during infantry dismount operations was near zero percent on the Fire Moth, compared to nearly seven percent on standard biped frames. The upper-mounted arms also facilitated Elemental deployment from the sides, making the design ideal for swift battlefield insertion of armored infantry.</p><p>Both the Ghost Bears and Hell's Horses make extensive use of the Fire Moth for reconnaissance, dueling, and infantry support. Because the design is poorly armed and infantry support is considered a lackluster assignment, the Fire Moth is frequently assigned to older warriors who lack Bloodnames before reaching solahma status. These warriors tend to be extremely aggressive, lending the Fire Moth a reputation that belies its modest armament.</p><p>Following Operation Revival and the Ghost Bears' migration to the Inner Sphere, the Dominion relocated its Fire Moth production lines from the Clan Homeworlds to Dominion Facility Kappa-4 on Goito and Dominion Facility Kappa-5 on Thule. The Goito facility was subsequently destroyed by Word of Blake agents in 3081 during the final stages of the Jihad, leaving Thule as the primary Inner Sphere production site. The Diamond Sharks facilitated trade of newer upgrades to the Exiled Wolves, who also adopted the design for infantry support missions.</p><p>In the Clan Homeworlds, the Fire Moth fell from favor during the Wars of Reaving, as remaining Home Clans increasingly associated it with the Inner Sphere-bound Ghost Bears. The Phantom OmniMech gradually supplanted it in Homeworld service, offering comparable speed with superior armor protection. Despite this decline in Clan Space, centuries of constant production, trade, and salvage have ensured that virtually all Clans have access to the Fire Moth, with most using it as a transport for Elementals, a fast scout, or a training 'Mech for unproven warriors.</p>

